# Architecture and Code Review Report
## Enterprise Asset Management System (Backend)

This report details the architectural and code quality audit of the Spring Boot backend project. The review covers Spring Boot best practices, Java 21 features, Spring Security integration, API design, database structures, and overall code design principles.

---

## 🔴 Critical Issues

### 1. Broken Spring Security Authorization (Empty Authorities)
* **File:** [CustomUserDetails.java](file:///c:/Users/YashRanjan/Desktop/Software%20Consulting/03_Projects/enterprise-asset-management-system/backend/src/main/java/com/yashconsulting/eams/security/CustomUserDetails.java#L19-L21)
* **Description:** 
  In `CustomUserDetails.java`, the `getAuthorities()` method is hardcoded to return an empty list:
  ```java
  @Override
  public Collection<? extends GrantedAuthority> getAuthorities() {
      return List.of();
  }
  ```
  Since `CustomUserDetailsService` wraps the loaded database user in `CustomUserDetails`, all authenticated users will reside in the security context with zero roles or authorities. This completely breaks role-based access control (RBAC), meaning security checks like `@PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')")` or request matching on roles will silently fail or reject all traffic.
* **Impact:** High vulnerability. Role checks will be completely ineffective.

### 2. Complete Absence of Endpoint-Level Security Controls
* **File:** [UserController.java](file:///c:/Users/YashRanjan/Desktop/Software%20Consulting/03_Projects/enterprise-asset-management-system/backend/src/main/java/com/yashconsulting/eams/user/controller/UserController.java)
* **Description:** 
  The controllers do not define any method-level authorization (such as `@PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')")`). In [SecurityConfig.java](file:///c:/Users/YashRanjan/Desktop/Software%20Consulting/03_Projects/enterprise-asset-management-system/backend/src/main/java/com/yashconsulting/eams/config/SecurityConfig.java#L54-L63), the HTTP rules are configured as:
  ```java
  .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
          .requestMatchers("/api/v1/auth/**", ...).permitAll()
          .anyRequest().authenticated()
  )
  ```
  This permits any authenticated user—regardless of role (e.g., standard `USER`)—full CRUD permissions on the user management endpoints. A standard user can list, update, and soft-delete user records (including admins).
* **Impact:** Critical privilege escalation vulnerability.

### 3. Missing Role Administration & Seeding Capabilities
* **Files:** [UserCreateRequest.java](file:///c:/Users/YashRanjan/Desktop/Software%20Consulting/03_Projects/enterprise-asset-management-system/backend/src/main/java/com/yashconsulting/eams/user/dto/UserCreateRequest.java), [UserUpdateRequest.java](file:///c:/Users/YashRanjan/Desktop/Software%20Consulting/03_Projects/enterprise-asset-management-system/backend/src/main/java/com/yashconsulting/eams/user/dto/UserUpdateRequest.java), and Flyway SQL migrations.
* **Description:** 
  The `UserCreateRequest` and `UserUpdateRequest` DTOs omit the `role` field. Consequently, any user created through the public API is default-assigned the `USER` role. Additionally, there are no Flyway database seed scripts (e.g. in [V1__Initial_Schema.sql](file:///c:/Users/YashRanjan/Desktop/Software%20Consulting/03_Projects/enterprise-asset-management-system/backend/src/main/resources/db/migration/V1__Initial_Schema.sql)) to provision an initial administrator account. Because of this, it is currently impossible to log in as an `ADMIN` or `MANAGER` without manual SQL database intervention.
* **Impact:** Inoperable administrative state out-of-the-box.

